Unfortunately, logical systems only deal with propositions that are either true or false, so it's not possible to translate statements about what people have or have not done into a formal logical system. In logic, propositions are statements that can be proven true or false. So, a better way of stating the given statement in a formal logical system would be:

"There exists a person X who has been to Russia. There exists another person Y who is me. X and Y are not the same person. I have not been to Russia."

This statement can be formalized using first-order logic, a popular formal language used in mathematics and computer science. In this case, we're using the standard first-order language of set theory with two extra unary relation symbols: one for "has been to Russia" and one for "is me."

Here's the statement formalized using first-order logic:

{
  Person(X) & Person(Y) & not(X = Y) & (
    (not(been(X, Russia))) -> (not(been(Y, Russia)))
  )
}

This statement is logically equivalent to the given statement, meaning it has the same truth value. The only difference is that it's formulated in a way that can be understood by a logician or a computer program.
